# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: high-performance-computing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] In computer architecture, **Amdahl's law** (or **Amdahl's argument**) is a formula limiting the speedup of a task as resources are added to the system executing that task.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] It is named after computer scientist Gene Amdahl, and was presented at the American Federation of Information Processing Societies (AFIPS) Spring Joint Computer Conference in 1967.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] Amdahl's law is often used in parallel computing to predict the theoretical speedup when using multiple processors.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] The ${\text{Speedup}}_{\text{overall}}$ is frequently much lower than one might expect.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] So, despite a massive improvement in one section, the overall benefit is quite small.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] In another example, if the programmer optimizes a section that accounts for 99% of the execution time (i.e. ${\text{Time}}_{\text{optimized}}$ of 0.99) with a speedup factor of 100 (i.e. ${\text{Speedup}}_{\text{optimized}}$ of 100), the ${\text{Speedup}}_{\text{overall}}$ only reaches 50.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] This indicates that half of the potential performance gain ( ${\text{Speedup}}_{\text{overall}}$ will reach 100 if 100% of the execution time is covered) is lost due to the remaining 1% of execution time that was not improved.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] An example is a computer program that processes files.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] A part of that program may scan the directory of the disk and create a list of files internally in memory.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] After that, another part of the program passes each file to a separate thread for processing.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] The part that scans the directory and creates the file list cannot be sped up on a parallel computer, but the part that processes the files can.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] The execution time of the whole task before the improvement of the resources of the system is denoted as T .
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] It includes the execution time of the part that would not benefit from the improvement of the resources and the execution time of the one that would benefit from it.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] The fraction of the execution time of the task that would benefit from the improvement of the resources is denoted by p .
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] The one concerning the part that would not benefit from it is therefore $1-p$ .
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] It is the execution of the part that benefits from the improvement of the resources that is accelerated by the factor s after the improvement of the resources.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] If 30% of the execution time may be the subject of a speedup, *p* will be 0.3; if the improvement makes the affected part twice as fast, *s* will be 2.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] For example, assume that we are given a serial task which is split into four consecutive parts, whose percentages of execution time are *p*1 = 0.11, *p*2 = 0.18, *p*3 = 0.23, and *p*4 = 0.48 respectively.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] Then we are told that the 1st part is not sped up, so *s*1 = 1, while the 2nd part is sped up 5 times, so *s*2 = 5, the 3rd part is sped up 20 times, so *s*3 = 20, and the 4th part is sped up 1.6 times, so *s*4 = 1.6.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] Notice how the 5 times and 20 times speedup on the 2nd and 3rd parts respectively don't have much effect on the overall speedup when the 4th part (48% of the execution time) is accelerated by only 1.6 times.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] Therefore, making part *A* to run 2 times faster is better than making part *B* to run 5 times faster.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] When $s=1$ , we have $S_{\text{latency}}(O,s)=1$ , meaning that the speedup is measured with respect to the execution time after the non-parallelizable part is optimized.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] Next, we consider the case wherein the non-parallelizable part is reduced by a factor of $O'$ , and the parallelizable part is correspondingly increased.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] Amdahl's law is often conflated with the law of diminishing returns, whereas only a special case of applying Amdahl's law demonstrates the law of diminishing returns.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] If one picks optimally (in terms of the achieved speedup) what is to be improved, then one will see monotonically decreasing improvements as one improves.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] If, however, one picks non-optimally, after improving a sub-optimal component and moving on to improve a more optimal component, one can see an increase in the return.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] Note that it is often rational to improve a system in an order that is "non-optimal" in this sense, given that some improvements are more difficult or require larger development time than others.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] Amdahl's law does represent the law of diminishing returns if one is considering what sort of return one gets by adding more processors to a machine, if one is running a fixed-size computation that will use all available processors to their capacity.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] Each new processor added to the system will add less usable power than the previous one.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] Each time one doubles the number of processors the speedup ratio will diminish, as the total throughput heads toward the limit of 1/(1 − *p*).
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] This analysis neglects other potential bottlenecks such as memory bandwidth and I/O bandwidth.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] If these resources do not scale with the number of processors, then merely adding processors provides even lower returns.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] An implication of Amdahl's law is that to speed up real applications which have both serial and parallel portions, heterogeneous computing techniques are required.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] There are novel speedup and energy consumption models based on a more general representation of heterogeneity, referred to as the normal form heterogeneity, that support a wide range of heterogeneous many-core architectures.
[src:high-performance-computing/amdahl-s-law] These modelling methods aim to predict system power efficiency and performance ranges, and facilitates research and development at the hardware and system software levels.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] CUDA is both a software layer that manages data, giving direct access to the GPU and CPU as necessary, and a library of APIs that enable parallel computation for various needs.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] In addition to drivers and runtime kernels, the CUDA platform includes compilers, libraries and developer tools to help programmers accelerate their applications.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] CUDA is written in the C programming language but is designed to work with a wide array of other programming languages including C++, Fortran, Python and Julia.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] This accessibility makes it easier for specialists in parallel programming to use GPU resources, in contrast to prior APIs like Direct3D and OpenGL, which require advanced skills in graphics programming.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] CUDA-powered GPUs also support programming frameworks such as OpenMP, OpenACC and OpenCL.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] The graphics processing unit (GPU), as a specialized computer processor, addresses the demands of real-time high-resolution 3D graphics compute-intensive tasks.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] By 2012, GPUs had evolved into highly parallel multi-core systems allowing efficient manipulation of large blocks of data.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] The origins of CUDA trace to the early 2000s, when Ian Buck, a computer science Ph.D. student at Stanford University, began experimenting with using GPUs for purposes beyond rendering graphics.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] Buck had first become interested in GPUs during his undergraduate studies at Princeton University, initially through video gaming.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] After graduation, he interned at Nvidia, gaining deeper exposure to GPU architecture.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] At Stanford, he built an 8K gaming rig using 32 GeForce graphics cards, originally to push the limits of graphics performance in games like Quake and Doom.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] However, his interests shifted toward exploring the potential of GPUs for general-purpose parallel computing.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] To that end, Buck developed Brook, a programming language designed to enable general-purpose computing on GPUs.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] His work attracted support from both Nvidia and the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA).
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] In 2004, Nvidia hired Buck and paired him with John Nickolls, the company's director of architecture for GPU computing.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] Together, they began transforming Brook into what would become CUDA.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] CUDA was officially released by Nvidia in 2007.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] Under the leadership of Nvidia CEO Jensen Huang, CUDA became central to the company's strategy of positioning GPUs as versatile hardware for scientific applications.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] By 2015, CUDA's development increasingly focused on accelerating machine learning and artificial neural network workloads.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] The following table offers a non-exact description for the ontology of the CUDA framework.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] The CUDA platform is accessible to software developers through CUDA-accelerated libraries, compiler directives such as OpenACC, and extensions to industry-standard programming languages including C, C++, Fortran and Python.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] C/C++ programmers can use 'CUDA C/C++', compiled to PTX with nvcc (Nvidia's LLVM-based C/C++ compiler) or by clang itself.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] Fortran programmers can use 'CUDA Fortran', compiled with the PGI CUDA Fortran compiler from The Portland Group.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] Python programmers can use the cuPyNumeric library to accelerate applications on Nvidia GPUs.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] In addition to libraries, compiler directives, CUDA C/C++ and CUDA Fortran, the CUDA platform supports other computational interfaces, including the Khronos Group's OpenCL, Microsoft's DirectCompute, OpenGL Compute Shader and C++ AMP.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] Third party wrappers are also available for Python, Perl, Fortran, Java, Ruby, Lua, Common Lisp, Haskell, R, MATLAB, IDL, Julia, and native support in Mathematica.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] In the computer game industry, GPUs are used for graphics rendering, and for game physics calculations (physical effects such as debris, smoke, fire, fluids); examples include PhysX and Bullet.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] CUDA has also been used to accelerate non-graphical applications in computational biology, cryptography and other fields by an order of magnitude or more.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] CUDA provides both a low level API (CUDA **Driver** API, non single-source) and a higher level API (CUDA **Runtime** API, single-source).
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] The initial CUDA SDK was made public on 15 February 2007, for Microsoft Windows and Linux.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] Mac OS X support was later added in version 2.0, which supersedes the beta released February 14, 2008.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] CUDA works with all Nvidia GPUs from the G8x series onwards, including GeForce, Quadro and the Tesla line.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] CUDA is compatible with most standard operating systems.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] Below is an example given in Python that computes the product of two arrays on the GPU.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] The unofficial Python language bindings can be obtained from *PyCUDA*.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] Additional Python bindings to simplify matrix multiplication operations can be found in the program *pycublas*.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] Note on notation: compute capability X.Y is also written as SMXY or sm_XY (e.g.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] 10.3 as SM103 or sm_103) in professional Nvidia software and the code Nvidia has contributed to LLVM.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] Note: CUDA SDK 10.2 is the last official release for macOS, as support will not be available for macOS in newer releases.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] Note: A GPU with a higher compute capacity is able to execute PTX code meant for a GPU of a lower range of compute capacities.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] However, it is possible to compile CUDA code into a form that only works on one family (same "X") of GPUs; if existing code is compiled this way, recompilation will be needed for it to work on a newer GPU.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] Note: Any missing lines or empty entries do reflect some lack of information on that exact item.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] For more information read the Nvidia CUDA C++ Programming Guide.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] CUDA competes with other GPU computing stacks: Intel OneAPI and AMD ROCm.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] Whereas Nvidia's CUDA is closed-source, Intel's OneAPI and AMD's ROCm are open source.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] Originally made by Intel, other hardware adopters include Fujitsu and Huawei.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] The goal is to offer open alternatives to Nvidia's CUDA.
[src:high-performance-computing/cuda] The main companies behind it are Intel, Google, ARM, Qualcomm, Samsung, Imagination, and VMware.
[src:high-performance-computing/distributed-memory] In computer science, **distributed memory** refers to a multiprocessor computer system in which each processor has its own private memory.
[src:high-performance-computing/distributed-memory] Computational tasks can only operate on local data, and if remote data are required, the computational task must communicate with one or more remote processors.
[src:high-performance-computing/distributed-memory] In contrast, a shared memory multiprocessor offers a single memory space used by all processors.
[src:high-performance-computing/distributed-memory] Processors do not have to be aware where data resides, except that there may be performance penalties, and that race conditions are to be avoided.
[src:high-performance-computing/distributed-memory] In a distributed memory system there is typically a processor, a memory, and some form of interconnection that allows programs on each processor to interact with each other.
[src:high-performance-computing/distributed-memory] The interconnect can be organised with point to point links or separate hardware can provide a switching network.
[src:high-performance-computing/distributed-memory] The network topology is a key factor in determining how the multiprocessor machine scales.
[src:high-performance-computing/distributed-memory] The links between nodes can be implemented using some standard network protocol (for example Ethernet), using bespoke network links (used in for example the transputer), or using dual-ported memories.
[src:high-performance-computing/distributed-memory] The key issue in programming distributed memory systems is how to distribute the data over the memories.
[src:high-performance-computing/distributed-memory] Depending on the problem solved, the data can be distributed statically, or it can be moved through the nodes.
[src:high-performance-computing/distributed-memory] Data can be moved on demand, or data can be pushed to the new nodes in advance.
[src:high-performance-computing/distributed-memory] As an example, if a problem can be described as a pipeline where data *x* is processed subsequently through functions *f*, *g*, *h*, etc.
[src:high-performance-computing/distributed-memory] (the result is *h*(*g*(*f*(*x*)))), then this can be expressed as a distributed memory problem where the data is transmitted first to the node that performs *f* that passes the result onto the second node that computes *g*, and finally to the third node that computes *h*.
[src:high-performance-computing/distributed-memory] This is also known as systolic computation.
[src:high-performance-computing/distributed-memory] Data can be kept statically in nodes if most computations happen locally, and only changes on edges have to be reported to other nodes.
[src:high-performance-computing/distributed-memory] An example of this is simulation where data is modeled using a grid, and each node simulates a small part of the larger grid.
[src:high-performance-computing/distributed-memory] On every iteration, nodes inform all neighboring nodes of the new edge data.
[src:high-performance-computing/distributed-memory] Similarly, in distributed shared memory each node of a cluster has access to a large shared memory in addition to each node's limited non-shared private memory.
[src:high-performance-computing/distributed-memory] Distributed shared memory hides the mechanism of communication, it does not hide the latency of communication.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Essentially, a GPGPU pipeline is a kind of parallel processing between one or more GPUs and CPUs, with special accelerated instructions for processing image or other graphic forms of data.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] While GPUs operate at lower frequencies, they typically have many times the number of processing elements.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Thus, GPUs can process far more pictures and other graphical data per second than a traditional CPU.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Migrating data into parallel form and then using the GPU to process it can (theoretically) create a large speedup.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU pipelines were developed at the beginning of the 21st century for graphics processing (e.g. for better shaders).
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] From the history of supercomputing it is well-known that scientific computing drives the largest concentrations of Computing power in history, listed in the TOP500: the majority today utilize GPUs.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The best-known GPGPUs are Nvidia Tesla that are used for Nvidia DGX, alongside AMD Instinct and Intel Gaudi.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In principle, any arbitrary Boolean function, including addition, multiplication, and other mathematical functions, can be built up from a functionally complete set of logic operators.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In 1987, Conway's Game of Life became one of the first examples of general-purpose computing using an early stream processor called a blitter to invoke a special sequence of logical operations on bit vectors.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] General-purpose computing on GPUs became more practical and popular after about 2001, with the advent of both programmable shaders and floating point support on graphics processors.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Notably, problems involving matrices and/or vectors – especially two-, three-, or four-dimensional vectors – were easy to translate to a GPU, which acts with native speed and support on those types.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A significant milestone for GPGPU was the year 2003 when two research groups independently discovered GPU-based approaches for the solution of general linear algebra problems on GPUs that ran faster than on CPUs.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] These early efforts to use GPUs as general-purpose processors required reformulating computational problems in terms of graphics primitives, as supported by the two major APIs for graphics processors, OpenGL and Direct3D.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This cumbersome translation was obviated by the advent of general-purpose programming languages and APIs such as Sh/RapidMind, Brook and Accelerator.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] These were followed by Nvidia's CUDA, which allowed programmers to ignore the underlying graphical concepts in favor of more common high-performance computing concepts.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Newer, hardware-vendor-independent offerings include Microsoft's DirectCompute and Apple/Khronos Group's OpenCL.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This means that modern GPGPU pipelines can leverage the speed of a GPU without requiring full and explicit conversion of the data to a graphical form.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Mark Harris, the founder of GPGPU.org, claims he coined the term *GPGPU*.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Any language that allows the code running on the CPU to poll a GPU shader for return values, can create a GPGPU framework.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Programming standards for parallel computing include OpenCL (vendor-independent), OpenACC, OpenMP and OpenHMPP.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] As of 2016, OpenCL is the dominant open general-purpose GPU computing language, and is an open standard defined by the Khronos Group.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenCL provides a cross-platform GPGPU platform that additionally supports data parallel compute on CPUs.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenCL is actively supported on Intel, AMD, Nvidia, and ARM platforms.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The Khronos Group has also standardised and implemented SYCL, a higher-level programming model for OpenCL as a single-source domain specific embedded language based on pure C++11.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The dominant proprietary framework is Nvidia CUDA.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Nvidia launched CUDA in 2006, a software development kit (SDK) and application programming interface (API) that allows using the programming language C to code algorithms for execution on GeForce 8 series and later GPUs.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] ROCm, launched in 2016, is AMD's open-source response to CUDA.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is, as of 2022, on par with CUDA with regards to features, and still lacking in consumer support.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenVIDIA was developed at University of Toronto between 2003–2005, in collaboration with Nvidia.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Altimesh Hybridizer created by Altimesh compiles Common Intermediate Language to CUDA binaries.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It supports generics and virtual functions.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Debugging and profiling is integrated with Visual Studio and Nsight.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is available as a Visual Studio extension on Visual Studio Marketplace.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Microsoft introduced the DirectCompute GPU computing API, released with the Direct3D 11 API.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] MATLAB supports GPGPU acceleration using the *Parallel Computing Toolbox* and *MATLAB Distributed Computing Server*, and third-party packages like Jacket.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU processing is also used to simulate Newtonian physics by physics engines, and commercial implementations include Havok Physics, FX and PhysX, both of which are typically used for computer and video games.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] C++ Accelerated Massive Parallelism (C++ AMP) is a library that accelerates execution of C++ code by exploiting the data-parallel hardware on GPUs.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Due to a trend of increasing power of mobile GPUs, general-purpose programming became available also on the mobile devices running major mobile operating systems.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Google Android 4.2 enabled running RenderScript code on the mobile device GPU.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] RenderScript has since been deprecated in favour of first OpenGL compute shaders and later Vulkan Compute.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenCL is available on many Android devices, but is not officially supported by Android.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Apple introduced the proprietary Metal API for iOS applications, able to execute arbitrary code through Apple's GPU compute shaders.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Originally, data was simply passed one-way from a central processing unit (CPU) to a graphics processing unit (GPU), then to a display device.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] As time progressed, however, it became valuable for GPUs to store at first simple, then complex structures of data to be passed back to the CPU that analyzed an image, or a set of scientific-data represented as a 2D or 3D format that a video card can understand.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Transferring the portion of the data set to be actively analyzed to that GPU memory in the form of textures or other easily readable GPU forms results in speed increase.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The distinguishing feature of a GPGPU design is the ability to transfer information bidirectionally back from the GPU to the CPU; generally the data throughput in both directions is ideally high, resulting in a multiplier effect on the speed of a specific high-use algorithm.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU pipelines may improve efficiency on especially large data sets and/or data containing 2D or 3D imagery.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is used in complex graphics pipelines as well as scientific computing; more so in fields with large data sets like genome mapping, or where two- or three-dimensional analysis is useful – especially at present biomolecule analysis, protein study, and other complex organic chemistry.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] An example of such applications is NVIDIA software suite for genome analysis.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Such pipelines can also vastly improve efficiency in image processing and computer vision, among other fields; as well as parallel processing generally.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some very heavily optimized pipelines have yielded speed increases of several hundred times the original CPU-based pipeline on one high-use task.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A simple example would be a GPU program that collects data about average lighting values as it renders some view from either a camera or a computer graphics program back to the main program on the CPU, so that the CPU can then make adjustments to the overall screen view.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A more advanced example might use edge detection to return both numerical information and a processed image representing outlines to a computer vision program controlling, say, a mobile robot.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU as a software concept is a type of algorithm, not a piece of equipment.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Specialized equipment designs may, however, even further enhance the efficiency of GPGPU pipelines, which traditionally perform relatively few algorithms on very large amounts of data.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Massively parallelized, gigantic-data-level tasks thus may be parallelized even further via specialized setups such as rack computing (many similar, highly tailored machines built into a *rack*), which adds a third layer – many computing units each using many CPUs to correspond to many GPUs.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some Bitcoin "miners" used such setups for high-quantity processing.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Insights into the largest such systems in the world has been maintained at the TOP500 supercomputer list.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Historically, CPUs have used hardware-managed caches, but the earlier GPUs only provided software-managed local memories.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] However, as GPUs are being increasingly used for general-purpose applications, state-of-the-art GPUs are being designed with hardware-managed multi-level caches which have helped the GPUs to move towards mainstream computing.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For example, GeForce 200 series GT200 architecture GPUs did not feature an L2 cache, the Fermi GPU has 768 KiB last-level cache, the Kepler GPU has 1.5 MiB last-level cache, the Maxwell GPU has 2 MiB last-level cache, and the Pascal GPU has 4 MiB last-level cache.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPUs have very large register files, which allow them to reduce context-switching latency.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Register file size is also increasing over different GPU generations, e.g., the total register file size on Maxwell (GM200), Pascal and Volta GPUs are 6 MiB, 14 MiB and 20 MiB, respectively.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] By comparison, the size of a register file on CPUs is small, typically tens or hundreds of kilobytes.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In essence: almost all GPU workloads are inherently massively-parallel LOAD-COMPUTE-STORE in nature, such as tiled rendering.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Even storing one temporary vector for further recall (LOAD-COMPUTE-STORE-COMPUTE-LOAD-COMPUTE-STORE) is so expensive due to the memory wall problem that it is to be avoided at all costs.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The result is that register file size *has* to increase.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In standard CPUs it is possible to introduce caches (a D-cache) to solve this problem, however these are relativrly so large that they are impractical to introduce in GPUs which would need one per processing element.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] ILLIAC IV innovatively solved the problem around 1967 by introducing a local memory per processing element (a PEM): a strategy copied by the Aspex ASP.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Much like how CPUs may elect to implement wider vector instructions in smaller pieces (e.g.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] AMD Bulldozer supported the 256-bit AVX instructions by splitting them into two 128-bit operations) to save power and/or chip area, GPU designers also vary the amount of execution units to fit their expected workloads.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] On a GPGPU, each of the following resources can vary freely in ratio from the others: FP64 (FMA), FP32 (FMA), FP16 (FMA), Int32 Add, Int32 Mul, RCP/RSQRT.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] (An example can be seen in Nvidia's documentation about the execution resources found in each SM of different generation (compute capacity) of GPUs.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is therefore insufficient to simply qualify a GPU's computational capabilities in terms of FLOPS: FLOPS values should be separately presented for matrix vs non-matrix modes and (T)OPS figures should also be presented for integer operations.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The high performance of GPUs comes at the cost of high power consumption, which under full load is in fact as much power as the rest of the PC system combined.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The maximum power consumption of the Pascal series GPU (Tesla P100) was specified to be 250W.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In terms of raw computing power (FLOPS, TOPS, etc.), GPUs tend to have more performance-per-watt than a typical CPU.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] However, it takes a well-written program and a fitting workload to extract most of this power, as most of the time (and power) would otherwise be wasted on local and host memory access.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Before CUDA was published in 2007, GPGPU was "classical" and involved repurposing graphics primitives.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] More examples are available in part 4 of *GPU Gems 2*.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Using GPU for numerical linear algebra began at least in 2001.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It had been used for Gauss-Seidel solver, conjugate gradients, etc.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Computer video cards are produced by various vendors, such as Nvidia, AMD.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Cards from such vendors differ on implementing data-format support, such as integer and floating-point formats (32-bit and 64-bit).
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Microsoft introduced a *Shader Model* standard, to help rank the various features of graphic cards into a simple Shader Model version number (1.0, 2.0, 3.0, etc.).
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Pre-Direct3D 9 video cards only supported paletted or integer color types.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Sometimes another alpha value is added, to be used for transparency.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For early fixed-function or limited programmability graphics (i.e., up to and including Direct3D 8.1-compliant GPUs) this was sufficient because this is also the representation used in displays.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This representation does have certain limitations.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Given sufficient graphics processing power even graphics programmers would like to use better formats, such as floating point data formats, to obtain effects such as high-dynamic-range imaging.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Many GPGPU applications require floating point accuracy, which came with video cards conforming to the Direct3D 9 specification.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Direct3D 9 Shader Model 2.x suggested the support of two precision types: full and partial precision.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Full precision support could either be FP32 or FP24 (floating point 32- or 24-bit per component) or greater, while partial precision was FP16.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] ATI's Radeon R300 series of GPUs supported FP24 precision only in the programmable fragment pipeline (although FP32 was supported in the vertex processors) while Nvidia's NV30 series supported both FP16 and FP32; other vendors such as S3 Graphics and XGI supported a mixture of formats up to FP24.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The implementations of floating point on Nvidia GPUs are mostly IEEE compliant; however, this is not true across all vendors.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This has implications for correctness which are considered important to some scientific applications.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] While 64-bit floating point values (double precision float) are commonly available on CPUs, these are not universally supported on GPUs.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some GPU architectures sacrifice IEEE compliance, while others lack double-precision.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Efforts have occurred to emulate double-precision floating point values on GPUs; however, the speed tradeoff negates any benefit to offloading the computing onto the GPU in the first place.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Most operations on the GPU operate in a vectorized fashion: one operation can be performed on up to four values at once.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For example, if one color ⟨R1, G1, B1⟩ is to be modulated by another color ⟨R2, G2, B2⟩, the GPU can produce the resulting color ⟨R1*R2, G1*G2, B1*B2⟩ in one operation.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This functionality is useful in graphics because almost every basic data type is a vector (either 2-, 3-, or 4-dimensional).
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Examples include vertices, colors, normal vectors, and texture coordinates.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPUs are originally designed specifically for graphics and thus are very restrictive in operations and programming.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Due to their design, GPUs are only effective for problems that can be solved using stream processing and the hardware can only be used in certain ways.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In the early GPGPU age, GPUs can only process independent vertices and fragments, but can process many of them in parallel.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This is especially effective when the programmer wants to process many vertices or fragments in the same way.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In this sense, GPUs are stream processors – processors that can operate in parallel by running one kernel on many records in a stream at once.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Programmers would use graphics APIs (OpenGL or Direct3D) to perform general-purpose computation.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] With the introduction of the CUDA (Nvidia, 2007) and OpenCL (vendor-independent, 2008) general-purpose computing APIs, in new GPGPU codes it is no longer necessary to map the computation to graphics primitives.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The stream processing nature of GPUs remains valid regardless of the APIs used.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A *stream* is simply a set of records that require similar computation.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] *Kernels* are the functions that are applied to each element in the stream.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In the GPUs, *vertices* and *fragments* are the elements in streams and vertex and fragment shaders are the kernels to be run on them.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For each element we can only read from the input, perform operations on it, and write to the output.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is permissible to have multiple inputs and multiple outputs, but never a piece of memory that is both readable and writable.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Arithmetic intensity is defined as the number of operations performed per word of memory transferred.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is important for GPGPU applications to have high arithmetic intensity else the memory access latency will limit computational speedup.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Ideal GPGPU applications have large data sets, high parallelism, and minimal dependency between data elements.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In fact, a program can substitute a write only texture for output instead of the framebuffer.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This is done either through render-to-texture (RTT), render-to-backbuffer-copy-to-texture (RTBCTT), or the more recent stream-out.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The most common form for a stream to take in GPGPU is a 2D grid because this fits naturally with the rendering model built into GPUs.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Many computations naturally map into grids: matrix algebra, image processing, physically based simulation, and so on.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Since textures are used as memory, texture lookups are then used as memory reads.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Certain operations can be done automatically by the GPU because of this.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Compute kernels can be thought of as the body of loops.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] On the GPU, the programmer only specifies the body of the loop as the kernel and what data to loop over by invoking geometry processing.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For accurate technical information on this topic see Predication_(computer_architecture)#SIMD,_SIMT_and_vector_predication and ILLIAC IV "branching" (the term "predicate mask" did not exist in 1967).
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In sequential code it is possible to control the flow of the program using if-then-else statements and various forms of loops.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Such flow control structures have only recently been added to GPUs.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Conditional writes could be performed using a properly crafted series of arithmetic/bit operations, but looping and conditional branching were not possible.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Recent GPUs allow branching, but usually with a performance penalty.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Branching should generally be avoided in inner loops, whether in CPU or GPU code, and various methods, such as static branch resolution, pre-computation, predication, loop splitting, and Z-cull can be used to achieve branching when hardware support does not exist.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The map operation simply applies the given function (the kernel) to every element in the stream.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A simple example is multiplying each value in the stream by a constant (increasing the brightness of an image).
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The map operation is simple to implement on the GPU.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The programmer generates a fragment for each pixel on screen and applies a fragment program to each one.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The result stream of the same size is stored in the output buffer.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some computations require calculating a smaller stream (possibly a stream of only one element) from a larger stream.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This is called a reduction of the stream.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Generally, a reduction can be performed in multiple steps.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The results from the prior step are used as the input for the current step and the range over which the operation is applied is reduced until only one stream element remains.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Stream filtering is essentially a non-uniform reduction.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Filtering involves removing items from the stream based on some criteria.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The scan operation, also termed *parallel prefix sum*, takes in a vector (stream) of data elements and an (arbitrary) associative binary function '+' with an identity element 'i'.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] If the input is [a0, a1, a2, a3, ...], an *exclusive scan* produces the output [i, a0, a0 + a1, a0 + a1 + a2, ...], while an *inclusive scan* produces the output [a0, a0 + a1, a0 + a1 + a2, a0 + a1 + a2 + a3, ...] and does not require an identity to exist.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] While at first glance the operation may seem inherently serial, efficient parallel scan algorithms are possible and have been implemented on graphics processing units.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The scan operation has uses in e.g., quicksort and sparse matrix-vector multiplication.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The scatter operation is most naturally defined on the vertex processor.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The vertex processor is able to adjust the position of the vertex, which allows the programmer to control where information is deposited on the grid.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Other extensions are also possible, such as controlling how large an area the vertex affects.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The fragment processor cannot perform a direct scatter operation because the location of each fragment on the grid is fixed at the time of the fragment's creation and cannot be altered by the programmer.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] However, a logical scatter operation may sometimes be recast or implemented with another gather step.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A scatter implementation would first emit both an output value and an output address.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] An immediately following gather operation uses address comparisons to see whether the output value maps to the current output slot.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In dedicated compute kernels, scatter can be performed by indexed writes.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] After scatter reorders elements according to a map, gather can restore the order of the elements according to the map scatter used.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In dedicated compute kernels, gather may be performed by indexed reads.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In other shaders, it is performed with texture-lookups.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The sort operation transforms an unordered set of elements into an ordered set of elements.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The most common implementation on GPUs is using radix sort for integer and floating point data and coarse-grained merge sort and fine-grained sorting networks for general comparable data.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The search operation allows the programmer to find a given element within the stream, or possibly find neighbors of a specified element.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Mostly the search method used is binary search on sorted elements.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Nvidia recommended GPUs for this application.
[src:high-performance-computing/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Check with developer or ISV to obtain certification information.
[src:high-performance-computing/high-performance-computing] HPC integrates systems administration (including network and security knowledge), parallel computing and distributed computing into a multidisciplinary field that combines digital electronics, computer architecture, system software, programming languages, algorithms and computational techniques.
[src:high-performance-computing/high-performance-computing] HPC technologies are the tools and systems used to implement and create high performance computing systems.
[src:high-performance-computing/high-performance-computing] Since around 2005, HPC systems have shifted from supercomputing to computing clusters and grids.
[src:high-performance-computing/high-performance-computing] Because of the need of networking in clusters and grids, High Performance Computing Technologies are achieved by the use of a collapsed network backbone, because the collapsed backbone architecture is simple to troubleshoot and upgrades can be applied to a single router as opposed to multiple ones.
[src:high-performance-computing/high-performance-computing] HPC integrates with data analytics in AI engineering workflows to generate new data streams that increase a simulation's ability to answer the "what if" questions.
[src:high-performance-computing/high-performance-computing] The term is most commonly associated with computing used for scientific research or computational science.
[src:high-performance-computing/high-performance-computing] A related term, high-performance technical computing (HPTC), generally refers to the engineering applications of cluster-based computing (such as computational fluid dynamics and the building and testing of virtual prototypes).
[src:high-performance-computing/high-performance-computing] HPC has also been applied to business uses such as data warehouses, line of business (LOB) applications, and transaction processing.
[src:high-performance-computing/high-performance-computing] High-performance computing (HPC) as a term arose after the term "supercomputing".
[src:high-performance-computing/high-performance-computing] HPC is sometimes used as a synonym for supercomputing; but, in other contexts, "supercomputer" is used to refer to a more powerful subset of "high-performance computers", and the term "supercomputing" becomes a subset of "high-performance computing".
[src:high-performance-computing/high-performance-computing] The potential for confusion over the use of these terms is apparent.
[src:high-performance-computing/high-performance-computing] Because most current applications are not designed for HPC technologies but are retrofitted, they are not designed or tested for scaling to more powerful processors or machines.
[src:high-performance-computing/high-performance-computing] Since networking clusters and grids use multiple processors and computers, these scaling problems can cripple critical systems in future supercomputing systems.
[src:high-performance-computing/high-performance-computing] Therefore, either the existing tools do not address the needs of the high performance computing community or the HPC community is unaware of these tools.
[src:high-performance-computing/high-performance-computing] In government and research institutions, scientists simulate galaxy formation and evolution, fusion energy, and global warming, as well as work to create more accurate short- and long-term weather forecasts.
[src:high-performance-computing/high-performance-computing] The world's tenth most powerful supercomputer in 2008, IBM Roadrunner (located at the United States Department of Energy's Los Alamos National Laboratory) simulated the performance, safety, and reliability of nuclear weapons and certifies their functionality.
[src:high-performance-computing/high-performance-computing] TOP500 ranks the world's 500 fastest high-performance computers, as measured by the High Performance LINPACK (HPL) benchmark.
[src:high-performance-computing/high-performance-computing] Not all existing computers are ranked, either because they are ineligible (e.g., they cannot run the HPL benchmark) or because their owners have not submitted an HPL score (e.g., because they do not wish the size of their system to become public information, for defense reasons).
[src:high-performance-computing/high-performance-computing] In addition, the use of the single LINPACK benchmark is controversial, in that no single measure can test all aspects of a high-performance computer.
[src:high-performance-computing/high-performance-computing] To help overcome the limitations of the LINPACK test, the U.S. government commissioned one of its originators, Jack Dongarra of the University of Tennessee, to create a suite of benchmark tests that includes LINPACK and others, called the HPC Challenge benchmark suite.
[src:high-performance-computing/high-performance-computing] This evolving suite has been used in some HPC procurements, but, because it is not reducible to a single number, it has been unable to overcome the publicity advantage of the less useful TOP500 LINPACK test.
[src:high-performance-computing/high-performance-computing] The TOP500 list is updated twice a year, once in June at the ISC European Supercomputing Conference and again at a US Supercomputing Conference in November.
[src:high-performance-computing/high-performance-computing] Many ideas for the new wave of grid computing were originally borrowed from HPC.
[src:high-performance-computing/high-performance-computing] Traditionally, HPC has involved an on-premises infrastructure, investing in supercomputers or computer clusters.
[src:high-performance-computing/high-performance-computing] Over the last decade, cloud computing has grown in popularity for offering computer resources in the commercial sector regardless of their investment capabilities.
[src:high-performance-computing/high-performance-computing] Some characteristics like scalability and containerization also have raised interest in academia.
[src:high-performance-computing/high-performance-computing] However security in the cloud concerns such as data confidentiality are still considered when deciding between cloud or on-premise HPC resources.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] In computer science, **parallelism** and concurrency are two different things: a parallel program uses multiple CPU cores, each core performing a task independently.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] On the other hand, concurrency enables a program to deal with multiple tasks even on a single CPU core; the core switches between tasks (i.e. threads) without necessarily completing each one.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] A program can have both, neither or a combination of parallelism and concurrency characteristics.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism, with multi-core and multi-processor computers having multiple processing elements within a single machine, while clusters, MPPs, and grids use multiple computers to work on the same task.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Specialized parallel computer architectures are sometimes used alongside traditional processors, for accelerating specific tasks.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Communication and synchronization between the different subtasks are typically some of the greatest obstacles to getting optimal parallel program performance.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] A theoretical upper bound on the speed-up of a single program as a result of parallelization is given by Amdahl's law, which states that it is limited by the fraction of time for which the parallelization can be utilised.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Traditionally, computer software has been written for serial computation.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] To solve a problem, an algorithm is constructed and implemented as a serial stream of instructions.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] These instructions are executed on a central processing unit on one computer.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Only one instruction may execute at a time—after that instruction is finished, the next one is executed.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Parallel computing, on the other hand, uses multiple processing elements simultaneously to solve a problem.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] This is accomplished by breaking the problem into independent parts so that each processing element can execute its part of the algorithm simultaneously with the others.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The processing elements can be diverse and include resources such as a single computer with multiple processors, several networked computers, specialized hardware, or any combination of the above.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Historically parallel computing was used for scientific computing and the simulation of scientific problems, particularly in the natural and engineering sciences, such as meteorology.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] This led to the design of parallel hardware and software, and high performance computing.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Frequency scaling was the dominant reason for improvements in computer performance from the mid-1980s until 2004.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The runtime of a program is equal to the number of instructions multiplied by the average time per instruction.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Maintaining everything else constant, increasing the clock frequency decreases the average time it takes to execute an instruction.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] An increase in frequency thus decreases runtime for all compute-bound programs.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] However, power consumption *P* by a chip is given by the equation *P* = *C* × *V* 2 × *F*, where *C* is the capacitance being switched per clock cycle (proportional to the number of transistors whose inputs change), *V* is voltage, and *F* is the processor frequency (cycles per second).
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Increases in frequency increase the amount of power used in a processor.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Increasing processor power consumption led ultimately to Intel's May 8, 2004 cancellation of its Tejas and Jayhawk processors, which is generally cited as the end of frequency scaling as the dominant computer architecture paradigm.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] To deal with the problem of power consumption and overheating the major central processing unit (CPU or processor) manufacturers started to produce power efficient processors with multiple cores.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The core is the computing unit of the processor and in multi-core processors each core is independent and can access the same memory concurrently.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Multi-core processors have brought parallel computing to desktop computers.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Thus parallelization of serial programs has become a mainstream programming task.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] In 2012 quad-core processors became standard for desktop computers, while servers had 10+ core processors.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Moore's law predicted that the number of cores per processor would double every 18–24 months.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] By 2023 some processors had over one hundred cores.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Some designs having a mix of performance and efficiency cores (such as ARM's big.LITTLE design) due to thermal and design constraints.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] An operating system can ensure that different tasks and user programs are run in parallel on the available cores.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] However, for a serial software program to take full advantage of the multi-core architecture the programmer needs to restructure and parallelize the code.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] A speed-up of application software runtime will no longer be achieved through frequency scaling, instead programmers will need to parallelize their software code to take advantage of the increasing computing power of multicore architectures.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Optimally, the speedup from parallelization would be linear—doubling the number of processing elements should halve the runtime, and doubling it a second time should again halve the runtime.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] However, very few parallel algorithms achieve optimal speedup.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Most of them have a near-linear speedup for small numbers of processing elements, which flattens out into a constant value for large numbers of processing elements.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The maximum potential speedup of an overall system can be calculated by Amdahl's law.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law indicates that optimal performance improvement is achieved by balancing enhancements to both parallelizable and non-parallelizable components of a task.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Furthermore, it reveals that increasing the number of processors yields diminishing returns, with negligible speedup gains beyond a certain point.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law has limitations, including assumptions of fixed workload, neglecting inter-process communication and synchronization overheads, primarily focusing on computational aspect and ignoring extrinsic factors such as data persistence, I/O operations, and memory access overheads.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Gustafson's law and Universal Scalability Law give a more realistic assessment of the parallel performance.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Understanding data dependencies is fundamental in implementing parallel algorithms.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] No program can run more quickly than the longest chain of dependent calculations (known as the critical path), since calculations that depend upon prior calculations in the chain must be executed in order.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] However, most algorithms do not consist of just a long chain of dependent calculations; there are usually opportunities to execute independent calculations in parallel.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Let *P**i* and *P**j* be two program segments.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions describe when the two are independent and can be executed in parallel.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] For *P**i*, let *I**i* be all of the input variables and *O**i* the output variables, and likewise for *P**j*.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Violation of the first condition introduces a flow dependency, corresponding to the first segment producing a result used by the second segment.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The second condition represents an anti-dependency, when the second segment produces a variable needed by the first segment.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The third and final condition represents an output dependency: when two segments write to the same location, the result comes from the logically last executed segment.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] In this example, instruction 3 cannot be executed before (or even in parallel with) instruction 2, because instruction 3 uses a result from instruction 2.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] It violates condition 1, and thus introduces a flow dependency.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] In this example, there are no dependencies between the instructions, so they can all be run in parallel.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions do not allow memory to be shared between different processes.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] For that, some means of enforcing an ordering between accesses is necessary, such as semaphores, barriers or some other synchronization method.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Subtasks in a parallel program are often called threads.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Some parallel computer architectures use smaller, lightweight versions of threads known as fibers, while others use bigger versions known as processes.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] However, "threads" is generally accepted as a generic term for subtasks.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Threads will often need synchronized access to an object or other resource, for example when they must update a variable that is shared between them.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Without synchronization, the instructions between the two threads may be interleaved in any order.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] If instruction 1B is executed between 1A and 3A, or if instruction 1A is executed between 1B and 3B, the program will produce incorrect data.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The programmer must use a lock to provide mutual exclusion.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] A lock is a programming language construct that allows one thread to take control of a variable and prevent other threads from reading or writing it, until that variable is unlocked.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The thread holding the lock is free to execute its critical section (the section of a program that requires exclusive access to some variable), and to unlock the data when it is finished.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] One thread will successfully lock variable V, while the other thread will be locked out—unable to proceed until V is unlocked again.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] This guarantees correct execution of the program.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Locks may be necessary to ensure correct program execution when threads must serialize access to resources, but their use can greatly slow a program and may affect its reliability.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Locking multiple variables using non-atomic locks introduces the possibility of program deadlock.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] An atomic lock locks multiple variables all at once.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] If it cannot lock all of them, it does not lock any of them.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] If two threads each need to lock the same two variables using non-atomic locks, it is possible that one thread will lock one of them and the second thread will lock the second variable.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] In such a case, neither thread can complete, and deadlock results.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Many parallel programs require that their subtasks act in synchrony.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Barriers are typically implemented using a lock or a semaphore.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] One class of algorithms, known as lock-free and wait-free algorithms, altogether avoids the use of locks and barriers.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] However, this approach is generally difficult to implement and requires correctly designed data structures.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Not all parallelization results in speed-up.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Generally, as a task is split up into more and more threads, those threads spend an ever-increasing portion of their time communicating with each other or waiting on each other for access to resources.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Once the overhead from resource contention or communication dominates the time spent on other computation, further parallelization (that is, splitting the workload over even more threads) increases rather than decreases the amount of time required to finish.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] This problem, known as parallel slowdown, can be improved in some cases by software analysis and redesign.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Applications are often classified according to how often their subtasks need to synchronize or communicate with each other.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] An application exhibits fine-grained parallelism if its subtasks must communicate many times per second; it exhibits coarse-grained parallelism if they do not communicate many times per second, and it exhibits embarrassing parallelism if they rarely or never have to communicate.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Embarrassingly parallel applications are considered the easiest to parallelize.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Flynn created one of the earliest classification systems for parallel (and sequential) computers and programs, now known as Flynn's taxonomy.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Flynn classified programs and computers by whether they were operating using a single set or multiple sets of instructions, and whether or not those instructions were using a single set or multiple sets of data.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-single-data (SISD) classification is equivalent to an entirely sequential program.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-multiple-data (SIMD) classification is analogous to doing the same operation repeatedly over a large data set.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] This is commonly done in signal processing applications.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-single-data (MISD) is a rarely used classification.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] While computer architectures to deal with this were devised (such as systolic arrays), few applications that fit this class materialized.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-multiple-data (MIMD) programs are by far the most common type of parallel programs.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Hennessy, "Some machines are hybrids of these categories, of course, but this classic model has survived because it is simple, easy to understand, and gives a good first approximation.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can incur significant overhead in practice, primarily due to the costs associated with merging data from multiple processes.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Specifically, inter-process communication and synchronization can lead to overheads that are substantially higher—often by two or more orders of magnitude—compared to processing the same data on a single thread.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Therefore, the overall improvement should be carefully evaluated.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] From the advent of very-large-scale integration (VLSI) computer-chip fabrication technology in the 1970s until about 1986, speed-up in computer architecture was driven by doubling computer word size—the amount of information the processor can manipulate per cycle.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Increasing the word size reduces the number of instructions the processor must execute to perform an operation on variables whose sizes are greater than the length of the word.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Historically, 4-bit microprocessors were replaced with 8-bit, then 16-bit, then 32-bit microprocessors.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] This trend generally came to an end with the introduction of 32-bit processors, which has been a standard in general-purpose computing for two decades.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Not until the early 2000s, with the advent of x86-64 architectures, did 64-bit processors become commonplace.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] A computer program is, in essence, a stream of instructions executed by a processor.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Without instruction-level parallelism, a processor can only issue less than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC < 1).
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *subscalar* processors.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] These instructions can be re-ordered and combined into groups which are then executed in parallel without changing the result of the program.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] This is known as instruction-level parallelism.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Advances in instruction-level parallelism dominated computer architecture from the mid-1980s until the mid-1990s.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] All modern processors have multi-stage instruction pipelines.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Each stage in the pipeline corresponds to a different action the processor performs on that instruction in that stage; a processor with an *N*-stage pipeline can have up to *N* different instructions at different stages of completion and thus can issue one instruction per clock cycle (IPC = 1).
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *scalar* processors.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The canonical example of a pipelined processor is a RISC processor, with five stages: instruction fetch (IF), instruction decode (ID), execute (EX), memory access (MEM), and register write back (WB).
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The Pentium 4 processor had a 35-stage pipeline.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Most modern processors also have multiple execution units.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] They usually combine this feature with pipelining and thus can issue more than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC > 1).
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *superscalar* processors.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Superscalar processors differ from multi-core processors in that the several execution units are not entire processors (i.e. processing units).
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Instructions can be grouped together only if there is no data dependency between them.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Scoreboarding and the Tomasulo algorithm (which is similar to scoreboarding but makes use of register renaming) are two of the most common techniques for implementing out-of-order execution and instruction-level parallelism.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Task parallelisms is the characteristic of a parallel program that "entirely different calculations can be performed on either the same or different sets of data".
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] This contrasts with data parallelism, where the same calculation is performed on the same or different sets of data.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Task parallelism involves the decomposition of a task into sub-tasks and then allocating each sub-task to a processor for execution.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The processors would then execute these sub-tasks concurrently and often cooperatively.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Task parallelism does not usually scale with the size of a problem.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Superword level parallelism is a vectorization technique based on loop unrolling and basic block vectorization.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] It is distinct from loop vectorization algorithms in that it can exploit parallelism of inline code, such as manipulating coordinates, color channels or in loops unrolled by hand.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Main memory in a parallel computer is either shared memory (shared between all processing elements in a single address space), or distributed memory (in which each processing element has its own local address space).
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Distributed memory refers to the fact that the memory is logically distributed, but often implies that it is physically distributed as well.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Distributed shared memory and memory virtualization combine the two approaches, where the processing element has its own local memory and access to the memory on non-local processors.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Accesses to local memory are typically faster than accesses to non-local memory.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] On the supercomputers, distributed shared memory space can be implemented using the programming model such as PGAS.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] This model allows processes on one compute node to transparently access the remote memory of another compute node.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] All compute nodes are also connected to an external shared memory system via high-speed interconnect, such as Infiniband, this external shared memory system is known as burst buffer, which is typically built from arrays of non-volatile memory physically distributed across multiple I/O nodes.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Computer architectures in which each element of main memory can be accessed with equal latency and bandwidth are known as uniform memory access (UMA) systems.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Typically, that can be achieved only by a shared memory system, in which the memory is not physically distributed.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] A system that does not have this property is known as a non-uniform memory access (NUMA) architecture.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Distributed memory systems have non-uniform memory access.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Computer systems (with the exception of Groq's LPUs) make use of caches—small and fast memories located close to the processor which store temporary copies of memory values (nearby in both the physical and logical sense).
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Parallel computer systems have difficulties with caches that may store the same value in more than one location, with the possibility of incorrect program execution.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] These computers require a cache coherency system, which keeps track of cached values and strategically purges them, thus ensuring correct program execution.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Bus snooping is one of the most common methods for keeping track of which values are being accessed (and thus should be purged).
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Designing large, high-performance cache coherence systems is a very difficult problem in computer architecture.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] As a result, shared memory computer architectures do not scale and distributed memory systems do.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Parallel computers based on interconnected networks need to have some kind of routing to enable the passing of messages between nodes that are not directly connected.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The medium used for communication between the processors is likely to be hierarchical in large multiprocessor machines.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] This classification is broadly analogous to the distance between basic computing nodes.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] These are not mutually exclusive; for example, clusters of symmetric multiprocessors are relatively common.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] A multi-core processor is a processor that includes multiple processing units (called "cores") on the same chip.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] IBM's Cell microprocessor, designed for use in the Sony PlayStation 3, is a prominent multi-core processor.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Each core in a multi-core processor can potentially be superscalar as well—that is, on every clock cycle, each core can issue multiple instructions from one thread.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Simultaneous multithreading (of which Intel's Hyper-Threading is the best known) was an early form of pseudo-multi-coreism.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] A processor capable of concurrent multithreading includes multiple execution units in the same processing unit—that is it has a superscalar architecture—and can issue multiple instructions per clock cycle from *multiple* threads.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Temporal multithreading on the other hand includes a single execution unit in the same processing unit and can issue one instruction at a time from *multiple* threads.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] A symmetric multiprocessor (SMP) is a computer system with multiple identical processors that share memory and connect via a bus.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Bus contention prevents bus architectures from scaling.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] As a result, SMPs generally do not comprise more than 32 processors.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Because of the small size of the processors and the significant reduction in the requirements for bus bandwidth achieved by large caches, such symmetric multiprocessors are extremely cost-effective, provided that a sufficient amount of memory bandwidth exists.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] A distributed computer (also known as a distributed memory multiprocessor) is a distributed memory computer system in which the processing elements are connected by a network.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Distributed computers are highly scalable.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have a lot of overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] A cluster is a group of loosely coupled computers that work together closely, so that in some respects they can be regarded as a single computer.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Clusters are composed of multiple standalone machines connected by a network.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] While machines in a cluster do not have to be symmetric, load balancing is more difficult if they are not.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The most common type of cluster is the Beowulf cluster, which is a cluster implemented on multiple identical commercial off-the-shelf computers connected with a TCP/IP Ethernet local area network.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Beowulf technology was originally developed by Thomas Sterling and Donald Becker.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] 87% of all Top500 supercomputers are clusters.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The remaining are Massively Parallel Processors, explained below.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Because grid computing systems (described below) can easily handle embarrassingly parallel problems, modern clusters are typically designed to handle more difficult problems—problems that require nodes to share intermediate results with each other more often.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] This requires a high bandwidth and, more importantly, a low-latency interconnection network.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Many historic and current supercomputers use customized high-performance network hardware specifically designed for cluster computing, such as the Cray Gemini network.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] As of 2014, most current supercomputers use some off-the-shelf standard network hardware, often Myrinet, InfiniBand, or Gigabit Ethernet.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] A massively parallel processor (MPP) is a single computer with many networked processors.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] MPPs have many of the same characteristics as clusters, but MPPs have specialized interconnect networks (whereas clusters use commodity hardware for networking).
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] MPPs also tend to be larger than clusters, typically having "far more" than 100 processors.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] In an MPP, "each CPU contains its own memory and copy of the operating system and application.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] IBM's Blue Gene/L, the fifth fastest supercomputer in the world according to the June 2009 TOP500 ranking, is an MPP.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Grid computing is the most distributed form of parallel computing.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] It makes use of computers communicating over the Internet to work on a given problem.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Because of the low bandwidth and extremely high latency available on the Internet, distributed computing typically deals only with embarrassingly parallel problems.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Most grid computing applications use middleware (software that sits between the operating system and the application to manage network resources and standardize the software interface).
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The most common grid computing middleware is the Berkeley Open Infrastructure for Network Computing (BOINC).
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Often volunteer computing software makes use of "spare cycles", performing computations at times when a computer is idling.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The ubiquity of the Internet and high-bandwidth networks enabled cloud computing, a model where massively parallel resources are provided as a service.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] This paradigm abstracts the underlying hardware, allowing users to access virtualized clusters for scalable workloads without managing physical infrastructure.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Modern distributed ledger protocols apply parallel computing principles to overcome the sequential bottlenecks of traditional blockchains.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] By sharding the state space, newer consensus architectures allow for "massively parallel transaction processing".
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] In this model, utilized by protocols such as Cerberus, independent transactions are treated as parallel tasks that can be executed simultaneously on different nodes, rather than being processed serially in a single global block.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Within parallel computing, there are specialized parallel devices that remain niche areas of interest.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] While not domain-specific, they tend to be applicable to only a few classes of parallel problems.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Reconfigurable computing is the use of a field-programmable gate array (FPGA) as a co-processor to a general-purpose computer.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] An FPGA is, in essence, a computer chip that can rewire itself for a given task.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] FPGAs can be programmed with hardware description languages such as VHDL or Verilog.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Several vendors have created C to HDL languages that attempt to emulate the syntax and semantics of the C programming language, with which most programmers are familiar.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The best known C to HDL languages are Mitrion-C, Impulse C, and Handel-C.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Specific subsets of SystemC based on C++ can also be used for this purpose.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] AMD's decision to open its HyperTransport technology to third-party vendors has become the enabling technology for high-performance reconfigurable computing.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] General-purpose computing on graphics processing units (GPGPU) is a fairly recent trend in computer engineering research.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] GPUs are co-processors that have been heavily optimized for computer graphics processing.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Computer graphics processing is a field dominated by data parallel operations—particularly linear algebra matrix operations.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] In the early days, GPGPU programs used the normal graphics APIs for executing programs.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] However, several new programming languages and platforms have been built to do general purpose computation on GPUs with both Nvidia and AMD releasing programming environments with CUDA and Stream SDK respectively.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Other GPU programming languages include BrookGPU, PeakStream, and RapidMind.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Nvidia has also released specific products for computation in their Tesla series.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The technology consortium Khronos Group has released the OpenCL specification, which is a framework for writing programs that execute across platforms consisting of CPUs and GPUs.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] AMD, Apple, Intel, Nvidia and others are supporting OpenCL.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Several application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) approaches have been devised for dealing with parallel applications.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Because an ASIC is (by definition) specific to a given application, it can be fully optimized for that application.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] As a result, for a given application, an ASIC tends to outperform a general-purpose computer.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] However, ASICs are created by UV photolithography.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] This process requires a mask set, which can be extremely expensive.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] A mask set can cost over a million US dollars.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] (The smaller the transistors required for the chip, the more expensive the mask will be.) Meanwhile, performance increases in general-purpose computing over time (as described by Moore's law) tend to wipe out these gains in only one or two chip generations.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] High initial cost, and the tendency to be overtaken by Moore's-law-driven general-purpose computing, has rendered ASICs unfeasible for most parallel computing applications.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] One example is the PFLOPS RIKEN MDGRAPE-3 machine which uses custom ASICs for molecular dynamics simulation.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] A vector processor is a CPU or computer system that can execute the same instruction on large sets of data.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Vector processors have high-level operations that work on linear arrays of numbers or vectors.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] An example vector operation is *A* = *B* × *C*, where *A*, *B*, and *C* are each 64-element vectors of 64-bit floating-point numbers.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] They are closely related to Flynn's SIMD classification.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Cray computers became famous for their vector-processing computers in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] However, vector processors—both as CPUs and as full computer systems—have generally disappeared.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Modern processor instruction sets do include some vector processing instructions, such as with Freescale Semiconductor's AltiVec and Intel's Streaming SIMD Extensions (SSE).
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Concurrent programming languages, libraries, APIs, and parallel programming models (such as algorithmic skeletons) have been created for programming parallel computers.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] These can generally be divided into classes based on the assumptions they make about the underlying memory architecture—shared memory, distributed memory, or shared distributed memory.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Shared memory programming languages communicate by manipulating shared memory variables.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Distributed memory uses message passing.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] POSIX Threads and OpenMP are two of the most widely used shared memory APIs, whereas Message Passing Interface (MPI) is the most widely used message-passing system API.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] One concept used in programming parallel programs is the future concept, where one part of a program promises to deliver a required datum to another part of a program at some future time.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Efforts to standardize parallel programming include an open standard called OpenHMPP for hybrid multi-core parallel programming.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The OpenHMPP directive-based programming model offers a syntax to efficiently offload computations on hardware accelerators and to optimize data movement to/from the hardware memory using remote procedure calls.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The rise of consumer GPUs has led to support for compute kernels, either in graphics APIs (referred to as compute shaders), in dedicated APIs (such as OpenCL), or in other language extensions.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Automatic parallelization of a sequential program by a compiler is the "holy grail" of parallel computing, especially with the aforementioned limit of processor frequency.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Despite decades of work by compiler researchers, automatic parallelization has had only limited success.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Mainstream parallel programming languages remain either explicitly parallel or (at best) partially implicit, in which a programmer gives the compiler directives for parallelization.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] A few fully implicit parallel programming languages exist—SISAL, Parallel Haskell, SequenceL, SystemC (for FPGAs), Mitrion-C, VHDL, and Verilog.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] As a computer system grows in complexity, the mean time between failures usually decreases.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing is a technique whereby the computer system takes a "snapshot" of the application—a record of all current resource allocations and variable states, akin to a core dump—; this information can be used to restore the program if the computer should fail.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing means that the program has to restart from only its last checkpoint rather than the beginning.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] While checkpointing provides benefits in a variety of situations, it is especially useful in highly parallel systems with a large number of processors used in high performance computing.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] As parallel computers become larger and faster, we are now able to solve problems that had previously taken too long to run.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Fields as varied as bioinformatics (for protein folding and sequence analysis) and economics have taken advantage of parallel computing.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can also be applied to the design of fault-tolerant computer systems, particularly via lockstep systems performing the same operation in parallel.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] This provides redundancy in case one component fails, and also allows automatic error detection and error correction if the results differ.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] These methods can be used to help prevent single-event upsets caused by transient errors.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Although additional measures may be required in embedded or specialized systems, this method can provide a cost-effective approach to achieve n-modular redundancy in commercial off-the-shelf systems.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The origins of true (MIMD) parallelism go back to Luigi Federico Menabrea and his *Sketch of the Analytic Engine Invented by Charles Babbage*.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] In 1957, Compagnie des Machines Bull announced the first computer architecture specifically designed for parallelism, the Gamma 60.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] It utilized a fork-join model and a "Program Distributor" to dispatch and collect data to and from independent processing units connected to a central memory.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] In April 1958, Stanley Gill (Ferranti) discussed parallel programming and the need for branching and waiting.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Also in 1958, IBM researchers John Cocke and Daniel Slotnick discussed the use of parallelism in numerical calculations for the first time.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Burroughs Corporation introduced the D825 in 1962, a four-processor computer that accessed up to 16 memory modules through a crossbar switch.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] In 1967, Amdahl and Slotnick published a debate about the feasibility of parallel processing at American Federation of Information Processing Societies Conference.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] It was during this debate that Amdahl's law was coined to define the limit of speed-up due to parallelism.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] In 1969, Honeywell introduced its first Multics system, a symmetric multiprocessor system capable of running up to eight processors in parallel.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] C.mmp, a multi-processor project at Carnegie Mellon University in the 1970s, was among the first multiprocessors with more than a few processors.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The first bus-connected multiprocessor with snooping caches was the Synapse N+1 in 1984.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] SIMD parallel computers can be traced back to the 1970s.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The motivation behind early SIMD computers was to amortize the gate delay of the processor's control unit over multiple instructions.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] In 1964, Slotnick had proposed building a massively parallel computer for the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] His design was funded by the US Air Force, which was the earliest SIMD parallel-computing effort, ILLIAC IV.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The key to its design was a fairly high parallelism, with up to 256 processors, which allowed the machine to work on large datasets in what would later be known as vector processing.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] However, ILLIAC IV was called "the most infamous of supercomputers", because the project was only one-fourth completed, but took 11 years and cost almost four times the original estimate.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] When it was finally ready to run its first real application in 1976, it was outperformed by existing commercial supercomputers such as the Cray-1.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] In the early 1970s, at the MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory, Marvin Minsky and Seymour Papert started developing the *Society of Mind* theory, which views the biological brain as massively parallel computer.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] In 1986, Minsky published *The Society of Mind*, which claims that "mind is formed from many little agents, each mindless by itself".
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] The theory attempts to explain how what we call intelligence could be a product of the interaction of non-intelligent parts.
[src:high-performance-computing/parallel-computing] Minsky says that the biggest source of ideas about the theory came from his work in trying to create a machine that uses a robotic arm, a video camera, and a computer to build with children's blocks.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] A **supercomputer** is a type of computer with a high level of performance as compared to a general-purpose computer.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] They have been essential in the field of cryptanalysis.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The performance of a supercomputer is commonly measured in floating-point operations per second (FLOPS) instead of million instructions per second (MIPS).
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Since 2022, exascale supercomputers have existed which can perform over 1018 FLOPS.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] For comparison, a desktop computer has performance in the range of hundreds of gigaFLOPS (1011) to tens of teraFLOPS (1013).
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Since November 2017, all of the world's fastest 500 supercomputers run on Linux-based operating systems.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Additional research is being conducted in the United States, the European Union, Taiwan, Japan, and China to build faster, more powerful and technologically superior exascale supercomputers.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Supercomputers were introduced in the 1960s, and for several decades the fastest was made by Seymour Cray at Control Data Corporation (CDC), Cray Research and subsequent companies bearing his name or monogram.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The first such machines were highly tuned conventional designs that ran quicker than their more general-purpose contemporaries.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Through the decade, increasing amounts of parallelism were added, with one to four processors being typical.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] In the 1970s, vector processors operating on large arrays of data came to dominate.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] A notable example is the highly successful Cray-1 of 1976.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Vector computers remained the dominant design into the 1990s.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] From then until today, massively parallel supercomputers with tens of thousands of off-the-shelf processors became the norm.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The U.S. has long been a leader in the supercomputer field, initially through Cray's nearly uninterrupted dominance, and later through a variety of technology companies.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Japan made significant advancements in the field during the 1980s and 1990s, while China has become increasingly active in supercomputing in recent years.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] As of November 2024, Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory's El Capitan is the world's fastest supercomputer.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The US has five of the top 10; Italy two, Japan, Finland, Switzerland have one each.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] In 1960, UNIVAC built the Livermore Atomic Research Computer (LARC), today considered among the first supercomputers, for the US Navy Research and Development Center.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] It still used high-speed drum memory, rather than the newly emerging disk drive technology.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Also, among the first supercomputers was the IBM 7030 Stretch.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The IBM 7030 was built by IBM for the Los Alamos National Laboratory, which then in 1955 had requested a computer 100 times faster than any existing computer.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The IBM 7030 used transistors, magnetic core memory, pipelined instructions, prefetched data through a memory controller and included pioneering random access disk drives.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The IBM 7030 was completed in 1961 and despite not meeting the challenge of a hundredfold increase in performance, it was purchased by the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Customers in England and France also bought the computer, and it became the basis for the IBM 7950 Harvest, a supercomputer built for cryptanalysis.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The third pioneering supercomputer project in the early 1960s was the Atlas at the University of Manchester, built by a team led by Tom Kilburn.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] He designed the Atlas to have memory space for up to a million words of 48 bits, but because magnetic storage with such a capacity was unaffordable, the actual core memory of the Atlas was only 16,000 words, with a drum providing memory for a further 96,000 words.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The Atlas Supervisor swapped data in the form of pages between the magnetic core and the drum.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The Atlas operating system also introduced time-sharing to supercomputing, so that more than one program could be executed on the supercomputer at any one time.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Atlas was a joint venture between Ferranti and Manchester University and was designed to operate at processing speeds approaching one microsecond per instruction, about one million instructions per second.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The CDC 6600, designed by Seymour Cray, was finished in 1964 and marked the transition from germanium to silicon transistors.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Silicon transistors could run more quickly and the overheating problem was solved by introducing refrigeration to the supercomputer design.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Thus, the CDC6600 became the fastest computer in the world.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Given that the 6600 outperformed all the other contemporary computers by about 10 times, it was dubbed a *supercomputer* and defined the supercomputing market, when one hundred computers were sold at $8 million each.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Cray left CDC in 1972 to form his own company, Cray Research.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Four years after leaving CDC, Cray delivered the 80 MHz Cray-1 in 1976, which became one of the most successful supercomputers in history.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] It had eight central processing units (CPUs), liquid cooling and the electronics coolant liquid Fluorinert was pumped through the supercomputer architecture.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] It reached 1.9 gigaFLOPS, making it the first supercomputer to break the gigaflop barrier.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The only computer to seriously challenge the Cray-1's performance in the 1970s was the ILLIAC IV.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] This machine was the first realized example of a true massively parallel computer, in which many processors worked together to solve different parts of a single larger problem.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] In contrast with the vector systems, which were designed to run a single stream of data as quickly as possible, in this concept, the computer instead feeds separate parts of the data to entirely different processors and then recombines the results.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The ILLIAC's design was finalized in 1966 with 256 processors and offer speed up to 1 GFLOPS, compared to the 1970s Cray-1's peak of 250 MFLOPS.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] However, development problems led to only 64 processors being built, and the system could never operate more quickly than about 200 MFLOPS while being much larger and more complex than the Cray.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Another problem was that writing software for the system was difficult, and getting peak performance from it was a matter of serious effort.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] But the partial success of the ILLIAC IV was widely seen as pointing the way to the future of supercomputing.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Cray argued against this, famously quipping that "If you were plowing a field, which would you rather use?
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Two strong oxen or 1024 chickens?" But by the early 1980s, several teams were working on parallel designs with thousands of processors, notably the Connection Machine (CM) that developed from research at MIT.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The CM-1 used as many as 65,536 simplified custom microprocessors connected together in a network to share data.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Several updated versions followed; the CM-5 supercomputer is a massively parallel processing computer capable of many billions of arithmetic operations per second.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] In 1982, Osaka University's LINKS-1 Computer Graphics System used a massively parallel processing architecture, with 514 microprocessors, including 257 Zilog Z8001 control processors and 257 iAPX 86/20 floating-point processors.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] It was mainly used for rendering realistic 3D computer graphics.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Fujitsu's VPP500 from 1992 is unusual since, to achieve higher speeds, its processors used GaAs, a material normally reserved for microwave applications due to its toxicity.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Fujitsu's Numerical Wind Tunnel supercomputer used 166 vector processors to gain the top spot in 1994 with a peak speed of 1.7 gigaFLOPS (GFLOPS) per processor.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The Hitachi SR2201 obtained a peak performance of 600 GFLOPS in 1996 by using 2048 processors connected via a fast three-dimensional crossbar network.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The Intel Paragon could have 1000 to 4000 Intel i860 processors in various configurations and was ranked the fastest in the world in 1993.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The Paragon was a MIMD machine which connected processors via a high speed two-dimensional mesh, allowing processes to execute on separate nodes, communicating via the Message Passing Interface.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Software development remained a problem, but the CM series sparked off considerable research into this issue.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Similar designs using custom hardware were made by many companies, including the Evans & Sutherland ES-1, MasPar, nCUBE, Intel iPSC and the Goodyear MPP.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] But by the mid-1990s, general-purpose CPU performance had improved so much in that a supercomputer could be built using them as the individual processing units, instead of using custom chips.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] By the turn of the 21st century, designs featuring tens of thousands of commodity CPUs were the norm, with later machines adding graphic units to the mix.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] In 1998, David Bader developed the first Linux supercomputer using commodity parts.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] While at the University of New Mexico, Bader sought to build a supercomputer running Linux using consumer off-the-shelf parts and a high-speed low-latency interconnection network.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The prototype utilized an Alta Technologies "AltaCluster" of eight dual, 333 MHz, Intel Pentium II computers running a modified Linux kernel.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Bader ported a significant amount of software to provide Linux support for necessary components as well as code from members of the National Computational Science Alliance (NCSA) to ensure interoperability, as none of it had been run on Linux previously.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Using the successful prototype design, he led the development of "RoadRunner," the first Linux supercomputer for open use by the national science and engineering community via the National Science Foundation's National Technology Grid.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] RoadRunner was put into production use in April 1999.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] At the time of its deployment, it was considered one of the 100 fastest supercomputers in the world.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Though Linux-based clusters using consumer-grade parts, such as Beowulf, existed prior to the development of Bader's prototype and RoadRunner, they lacked the scalability, bandwidth, and parallel computing capabilities to be considered "true" supercomputers.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Systems with a massive number of processors generally take one of two paths.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] In the grid computing approach, the processing power of many computers, organized as distributed, diverse administrative domains, is opportunistically used whenever a computer is available.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] In another approach, many processors are used in proximity to each other, e.g. in a computer cluster.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] In such a centralized massively parallel system the speed and flexibility of the *interconnect* becomes very important and modern supercomputers have used various approaches ranging from enhanced Infiniband systems to three-dimensional torus interconnects.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The use of multi-core processors combined with centralization is an emerging direction, e.g. as in the Cyclops64 system.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] As the price, performance and energy efficiency of general-purpose graphics processing units (GPGPUs) have improved, a number of petaFLOPS supercomputers such as Tianhe-I and Nebulae have started to rely on them.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] However, GPUs are gaining ground, and in 2012 the Jaguar supercomputer was transformed into Titan by retrofitting CPUs with GPUs.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] High-performance computers have an expected life cycle of about three years before requiring an upgrade.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The Gyoukou supercomputer is unique in that it uses both a massively parallel design and liquid immersion cooling.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] A number of special-purpose systems have been designed, dedicated to a single problem.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] This allows the use of specially programmed FPGA chips or even custom ASICs, allowing better price/performance ratios by sacrificing generality.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Examples of special-purpose supercomputers include Belle, Deep Blue, and Hydra for playing chess, Gravity Pipe for astrophysics, MDGRAPE-3 for protein structure prediction and molecular dynamics, and Deep Crack for breaking the DES cipher.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Throughout the decades, the management of heat density has remained a key issue for most centralized supercomputers.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The large amount of heat generated by a system may also have other effects, e.g. reducing the lifetime of other system components.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] There have been diverse approaches to heat management, from pumping Fluorinert through the system, to a hybrid liquid-air cooling system or air cooling with normal air conditioning temperatures.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] A typical supercomputer consumes large amounts of electrical power, almost all of which is converted into heat, requiring cooling.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] For example, Tianhe-1A consumes 4.04 megawatts (MW) of electricity.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The cost to power and cool the system can be significant, e.g.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] 4 MW at $0.10/kWh is $400 an hour or about $3.5 million per year.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Heat management is a major issue in complex electronic devices and affects powerful computer systems in various ways.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The thermal design power and CPU power dissipation issues in supercomputing surpass those of traditional computer cooling technologies.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The supercomputing awards for green computing reflect this issue.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The packing of thousands of processors together inevitably generates significant amounts of heat density that need to be dealt with.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The Cray-2 was liquid cooled, and used a Fluorinert "cooling waterfall" which was forced through the modules under pressure.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] However, the submerged liquid cooling approach was not practical for the multi-cabinet systems based on off-the-shelf processors, and in System X a special cooling system that combined air conditioning with liquid cooling was developed in conjunction with the Liebert company.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] In the Blue Gene system, IBM deliberately used low power processors to deal with heat density.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The IBM Power 775, released in 2011, has closely packed elements that require water cooling.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The IBM Aquasar system uses hot water cooling to achieve energy efficiency, the water being used to heat buildings as well.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The energy efficiency of computer systems is generally measured in terms of "FLOPS per watt".
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] In 2008, Roadrunner by IBM operated at 376 MFLOPS/W.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] In November 2010, the Blue Gene/Q reached 1684 MFLOPS/W and in June 2011 the top two spots on the Green 500 list were occupied by Blue Gene machines in New York (one achieving 2097 MFLOPS/W) with the DEGIMA cluster in Nagasaki placing third with 1375 MFLOPS/W.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Because copper wires can transfer energy into a supercomputer with much higher power densities than forced air or circulating refrigerants can remove waste heat, the ability of the cooling systems to remove waste heat is a limiting factor.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] As of 2015, many existing supercomputers have more infrastructure capacity than the actual peak demand of the machine – designers generally conservatively design the power and cooling infrastructure to handle more than the theoretical peak electrical power consumed by the supercomputer.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Since the end of the 20th century, supercomputer operating systems have undergone major transformations, based on the changes in supercomputer architecture.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] While early operating systems were custom tailored to each supercomputer to gain speed, the trend has been to move away from in-house operating systems to the adaptation of generic software such as Linux.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The parallel architectures of supercomputers often dictate the use of special programming techniques to exploit their speed.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Software tools for distributed processing include standard APIs such as MPI and PVM, VTL, and open source software such as Beowulf.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] In the most common scenario, environments such as PVM and MPI for loosely connected clusters and OpenMP for tightly coordinated shared memory machines are used.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Significant effort is required to optimize an algorithm for the interconnect characteristics of the machine it will be run on; the aim is to prevent any of the CPUs from wasting time waiting on data from other nodes.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] GPGPUs have hundreds of processor cores and are programmed using programming models such as CUDA or OpenCL.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Moreover, it is quite difficult to debug and test parallel programs.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Special techniques need to be used for testing and debugging such applications.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Opportunistic supercomputing is a form of networked grid computing whereby a "super virtual computer" of many loosely coupled volunteer computing machines performs very large computing tasks.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Grid computing has been applied to a number of large-scale embarrassingly parallel problems that require supercomputing performance scales.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] However, basic grid and cloud computing approaches that rely on volunteer computing cannot handle traditional supercomputing tasks such as fluid dynamic simulations.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The fastest grid computing system is the volunteer computing project Folding@home (F@h).
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] As of April 2020, F@h reported 2.5 exaFLOPS of x86 processing power.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Of this, over 100 PFLOPS are contributed by clients running on various GPUs, and the rest from various CPU systems.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The Berkeley Open Infrastructure for Network Computing (BOINC) platform hosts a number of volunteer computing projects.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] As of February 2017, BOINC recorded a processing power of over 166 petaFLOPS through over 762 thousand active Computers (Hosts) on the network.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] As of October 2016, Great Internet Mersenne Prime Search's (GIMPS) distributed Mersenne Prime search achieved about 0.313 PFLOPS through over 1.3 million computers.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The PrimeNet server has supported GIMPS's grid computing approach, one of the earliest volunteer computing projects, since 1997.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Quasi-opportunistic supercomputing is a form of distributed computing whereby the "super virtual computer" of many networked geographically disperse computers performs computing tasks that demand huge processing power.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Cloud computing with its recent and rapid expansions and development have grabbed the attention of high-performance computing (HPC) users and developers in recent years.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Cloud computing attempts to provide HPC-as-a-service exactly like other forms of services available in the cloud such as software as a service, platform as a service, and infrastructure as a service.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] HPC users may benefit from the cloud in different angles such as scalability, resources being on-demand, fast, and inexpensive.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] On the other hand, moving HPC applications have a set of challenges too.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Good examples of such challenges are virtualization overhead in the cloud, multi-tenancy of resources, and network latency issues.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Much research is currently being done to overcome these challenges and make HPC in the cloud a more realistic possibility.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] In 2016, Penguin Computing, Parallel Works, R-HPC, Amazon Web Services, Univa, Silicon Graphics International, Rescale, Sabalcore, and Gomput started to offer HPC cloud computing.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The Penguin On Demand (POD) cloud is a bare-metal compute model to execute code, but each user is given virtualized login node.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] POD computing nodes are connected via non-virtualized 10 Gbit/s Ethernet or QDR InfiniBand networks.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] User connectivity to the POD data center ranges from 50 Mbit/s to 1 Gbit/s.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Citing Amazon's EC2 Elastic Compute Cloud, Penguin Computing argues that virtualization of compute nodes is not suitable for HPC.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Penguin Computing has also criticized that HPC clouds may have allocated computing nodes to customers that are far apart, causing latency that impairs performance for some HPC applications.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Supercomputers generally aim for the maximum in capability computing rather than capacity computing.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Capability computing is typically thought of as using the maximum computing power to solve a single large problem in the shortest amount of time.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Often a capability system is able to solve a problem of a size or complexity that no other computer can, e.g. a very complex weather simulation application.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Capacity computing, in contrast, is typically thought of as using efficient cost-effective computing power to solve a few somewhat large problems or many small problems.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Architectures that lend themselves to supporting many users for routine everyday tasks may have a lot of capacity but are not typically considered supercomputers, given that they do not solve a single very complex problem.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] In general, the speed of supercomputers is measured and benchmarked in FLOPS (floating-point operations per second), and not in terms of MIPS (million instructions per second), as is the case with general-purpose computers.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Exascale is computing performance in the exaFLOPS (EFLOPS) range.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] An EFLOPS is one quintillion (1018) FLOPS (one million TFLOPS).
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] However, the performance of a supercomputer can be severely impacted by fluctuation brought on by elements like system load, network traffic, and concurrent processes, as mentioned by Brehm and Bruhwiler (2015).
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] No single number can reflect the overall performance of a computer system, yet the goal of the Linpack benchmark is to approximate how fast the computer solves numerical problems and it is widely used in the industry.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The LINPACK benchmark typically performs LU decomposition of a large matrix.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Since 1993, the fastest supercomputers have been ranked on the TOP500 list according to their LINPACK benchmark results.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The list does not claim to be unbiased or definitive, but it is a widely cited current definition of the "fastest" supercomputer available at any given time.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] This is a list of the computers which appeared at the top of the TOP500 list since June 1993, and the "Peak speed" is given as the "Rmax" rating.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] In 2018, Lenovo became the world's largest provider for the TOP500 supercomputers with 117 units produced.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The application of supercomputers has evolved significantly since the 1970s, expanding across numerous fields of scientific and governmental research.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] In the 1970s, the Cray-1 supercomputer was instrumental in early weather forecasting and aerodynamic research.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The scope broadened in the 1980s with machines like the CDC Cyber facilitating probabilistic analyses and modeling radiation shielding.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The 1990s saw supercomputers, such as the EFF DES cracker, applied to brute-force tasks like code-breaking.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Moving into the 2000s, supercomputers became crucial for national security applications; the ASCI Q was used to conduct 3D nuclear test simulations, satisfying the requirements of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty without physical testing.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The 2010s brought advancements in molecular dynamics simulations, exemplified by the use of the Tianhe-1A.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The trend has continued into the 2020s, with supercomputers providing powerful tools for research into outbreak prevention and electrochemical reactions.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Beyond these specific decades, supercomputers have been pivotal in major scientific endeavors.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] For instance, the IBM Blue Gene/P was used to simulate a network of artificial neurons equivalent to one percent of a human cerebral cortex (1.6 billion neurons and 9 trillion connections), and the same team later simulated the entirety of a rat's brain.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Modern applications are diverse and critical.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Weather forecasting relies heavily on supercomputing power, with the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration utilizing these systems to process vast quantities of observational data to enhance forecast accuracy.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The United States also employs supercomputers through the Advanced Simulation and Computing Program to maintain and simulate its nuclear stockpile.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The field has its challenges, as highlighted by IBM's abandonment of the ambitious Blue Waters petascale project in 2011.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Despite such setbacks, the utility of supercomputers continues to grow.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] A recent example of their critical role occurred in early 2020, when supercomputers were rapidly deployed to run extensive simulations using numerous paralleled CPUs to identify compounds with the potential to stop the spread of COVID-19.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] In the 2010s, China, the United States, the European Union, and others competed to be the first to create a 1 exaFLOP (1018 or one quintillion FLOPS) supercomputer.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] DeBenedictis of Sandia National Laboratories has theorized that a zettaFLOPS (1021 or one sextillion FLOPS) computer is required to accomplish full weather modeling, which could cover a two-week time span accurately.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Such systems might be built around 2030.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Many Monte Carlo simulations use the same algorithm to process a randomly generated data set; particularly, integro-differential equations describing physical transport processes, the random paths, collisions, and energy and momentum depositions of neutrons, photons, ions, electrons, etc.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The next step for microprocessors may be into the third dimension; and specializing to Monte Carlo, the many layers could be identical, simplifying the design and manufacture process.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The cost of operating high performance supercomputers has risen, mainly due to increasing power consumption.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] In the mid-1990s a top 10 supercomputer required in the range of 100 kilowatts, in 2010 the top 10 supercomputers required between 1 and 2 megawatts.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] A 2010 study commissioned by DARPA identified power consumption as the most pervasive challenge in achieving Exascale computing.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] At the time a megawatt per year in energy consumption cost about 1 million dollars.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Supercomputing facilities were constructed to efficiently remove the increasing amount of heat produced by modern multi-core central processing units.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Based on the energy consumption of the Green 500 list of supercomputers between 2007 and 2011, a supercomputer with 1 exaFLOPS in 2011 would have required nearly 500 megawatts.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Operating systems were developed for existing hardware to conserve energy whenever possible.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] CPU cores not in use during the execution of a parallelized application were put into low-power states, producing energy savings for some supercomputing applications.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The increasing cost of operating supercomputers has been a driving factor in a trend toward bundling of resources through a distributed supercomputer infrastructure.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] National supercomputing centers first emerged in the US, followed by Germany and Japan.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The European Union launched the Partnership for Advanced Computing in Europe (PRACE) with the aim of creating a persistent pan-European supercomputer infrastructure with services to support scientists across the European Union in porting, scaling and optimizing supercomputing applications.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Iceland built the world's first zero-emission supercomputer.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Located at the Thor Data Center in Reykjavík, Iceland, this supercomputer relies on completely renewable sources for its power rather than fossil fuels.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] The colder climate also reduces the need for active cooling, making it one of the greenest facilities in the world of computers.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Funding supercomputer hardware also became increasingly difficult.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] In the mid-1990s a top 10 supercomputer cost about 10 million euros, while in 2010 the top 10 supercomputers required an investment of between 40 and 50 million euros.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] In the 2000s national governments put in place different strategies to fund supercomputers.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] In the UK the national government funded supercomputers entirely and high performance computing was put under the control of a national funding agency.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Germany developed a mixed funding model, pooling local state funding and federal funding.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] Examples of supercomputers in fiction include HAL 9000, Multivac, The Machine Stops, GLaDOS, SHODAN, The Evitable Conflict, Vulcan's Hammer, Colossus, WOPR, AM, and Deep Thought.
[src:high-performance-computing/supercomputer] A supercomputer from Thinking Machines was mentioned as the supercomputer used to sequence the DNA extracted from preserved parasites in the Jurassic Park series.
